<stack-static>
    <statement><p><p>
Given that:
<me>
\log A = {0.4935}, \quad \log B = {0.4585}
</me>
</p>

<p>
Use logarithms to find the value of:
</p>

<p>
<me>
A \times B
</me>
</p>

<p>
Give your answer correct to 3 decimal places.
</p>

<p>
<fillin characters="15" name="ans1"/>  
</p></p></statement>
    <solution><p><h3>Worked Solution</h3>

<p>
Step 1: Use the product rule:
</p>

<p>
<me>
\text{log} (AB) = \text{log} A + \text{log} B
</me>
</p>

<p>
<me>
= {0.4935} + {0.4585}
</me>
</p>

<p>
<me>
= {0.952}
</me>
</p>

<p>
Step 2: Take the antilogarithm:
</p>

<p>
<me>
AB = 10^{0.952}
</me>
</p>

<p>
<me>
= {8.954}
</me>
</p></p></solution>
    <answer><p><m>8.954</m></p></answer>
</stack-static>